A Sound but Incomplete Fixpoint-Computation
Algorithm: The Ground Case
This section presents a heuristic algorithm based on a fixpoint operator Œì

which maps APT-programs to APT-programs and iteratively tightens the probability
bounds on rules and ptf‚Äôs in the program. To find probability bounds on some time
formula œÜ, we simply add the ptf œÜ : [0, 1] to the program, iteratively apply Œì until
a fixed point is reached, and then examine the bounds on the ptf formed with œÜ in
the resulting program. Our approach is sound ‚Äì so, if the interval [‚Ñì, u] is assigned
to œÜ, then K entails œÜ : [‚Ñì, u] (provided, of course, that K is consistent). However,
there may exist some [‚Ñì‚Ä≤ , u‚Ä≤ ] ‚äÇ [‚Ñì, u] such that œÜ : [‚Ñì‚Ä≤ , u‚Ä≤ ] is also entailed.
Our algorithm requires that K contain at least one APT-rule of the form

