Geospatial Abduction

In the previous two chapter, we explored temporal aspects of an agent‚Äôs behavior with APT logic. The next three chapters deal with spatial aspects of an
agent‚Äôs behavior. These chapters are primarily concerned with variants of geospatial abduction problems - inferring unobserved geospatial locations associated with
agent behavior. In this chapter, we formalize the idea of geopspatial abduction and
study some natural problems associated with this framework.1

4.1

Chapter Introduction
There are numerous applications where we wish to draw geospatial inferences

from observations. For example, criminologists [144, 15] have found that there
are spatial relationships between a serial killer‚Äôs house (the geospatial inference we
wish to make), and locations where the crimes were committed (the observations).
1

