Abstract‚ÄîSecurity organizations often attempt to disrupt terror or insurgent networks by targeting ‚Äúhigh value targets‚Äù
(HVT‚Äôs). However, there have been numerous examples that
illustrate how such networks are able to quickly re-generate
leadership after such an operation. Here, we introduce the notion
of a shaping operation in which the terrorist network is Ô¨Årst
targeted for the purpose of reducing its leadership re-generation
ability before targeting HVT‚Äôs. We look to conduct shaping by
maximizing the network-wide degree centrality through node
removal. We formally deÔ¨Åne this problem and prove solving it is
NP-Complete. We introduce a greedy heuristic for to approximate
this problem. We implement the greedy heuristic and found in
examining Ô¨Åve real-world terrorist networks that removing only
12% of nodes can increase the network-wide centrality between
17% and 45%.
