clustering problem seek only to arrange points in groups, with ‚Äúcenters‚Äù being a side
effect of the algorithm. Geospatial abduction problem seeks to find partners that support observations and places constraints on the location of the partners; this is a key
difference from ‚Äúcenters‚Äù in clustering problems. Clustering algorithms cannot handle
the generality of our feasibility predicate or the (Œ±, Œ≤) constraints.
