Conclusions

In this paper we described how to target nodes in a terrorist or insurgent network as part of a shaping operation designed to reduce the
organization‚Äôs ability to regenerate leadership. Our key intuition
was to increase the network-wide degree centrality which would
likely have the effect of eliminating emerging leaders as maximizing this quantity would intuitively increase the organization‚Äôs reliance on a single leader. In this paper, we found that though identifying a set of nodes to maximize this network-wide degree centrality is NP-hard, our greedy approach proved to be a viable heuristic for this problem, increasing this quantity between 17% ‚àí 45%
in our experiments. Future work could include an examination of
other types of network-wide centrality ‚Äì for instance network-wide
closeness centrality ‚Äì instead of network-wide degree centrality.
Another aspect that we are considering in ongoing research is determining the effectiveness of the shaping strategy when we have
observed only part of the terrorist or insurgent organization ‚Äì as is
often the case as such networks are created from intelligence data.
